{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:57:53.705Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing API Object Mapping**\n\nI'm currently focused on the relationship between `ApiAiOperation` objects from the backend and `EnrichedAgent` objects used in the client-side UI. I'm trying to determine whether we have separate mock lists for both, or if these two objects can be merged or enriched. My current focus is to understand how the `/api/v1/ai` endpoint's `ApiAiOperation` relates to client-side data.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:57:55.545Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Mapping Operation Attributes**\n\nI've been examining the attributes of `ApiAiOperation` more closely. I'm noting key fields such as `id`, `name`, `status`, `health`, and `agent_type`. I'm starting to see a possible mapping to the client-side `EnrichedAgent` structure, but it's not a perfect fit. I will need to consider how `client_id`, `client_name`, `project_id` and the other fields might relate.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:57:56.979Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Clarifying Client-Side Logic**\n\nI'm now focusing on how client-side user filtering works for the `/api/v1/ai-operations` endpoint. The task specifies that client users should only see their `client_id` records, and I've realized that the backend already implements this filtering based on the caller's role, through `/app/api/v1/ai-operations/route.ts`. This seems to simplify the client-side implementation significantly, but requires a good understanding of what the backend provides, like `ram`, `latency`, `uptime`.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:57:58.617Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Object Transformations**\n\nI've determined that the `/api/v1/ai-operations` endpoint *already* handles client-side filtering by `client_id` through JWT token! Now, the focus is on mapping `ApiAiOperation` objects to the client-side's `EnrichedAgent` format. I'm actively mapping fields like `id` and `name` from `ApiAiOperation` to `EnrichedAgent`. I'm starting to build a converter, to avoid altering Phase 4!\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:00.777Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining Project Mappings**\n\nI'm now focusing on mapping project IDs to more user-friendly names for the client. I've decided to use a lookup table for project IDs: `\"proj-001\"` becomes `\"Sovereign Core Sandbox 02\"`, `\"proj-002\"` to `\"Model Guardrail Sandbox 04\"`, etc., for clearer UI representation. If there isn't a defined ID, I'll use the `operation.project_id` or other title if available. I've decided to focus on cleaning and mapping the various statuses into a standard field in `EnrichedAgent`.\n\nI will be mapping various states to a unified `status` within the enriched agent object. Based on the underlying values of `status` or `health` I'm deciding if I will set it to `\"active\"`, `\"evaluating\"`, `\"warning\"` or `\"decoupled\"`\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:02.203Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Enriching Agent Types**\n\nI'm now focusing on dynamically enriching `EnrichedAgent` objects based on `agent_type`. If `agent_type` is \"autonomous\", I map it to \"Core Telemetry\" or \"Alignment Guard.\" \"human-in-the-loop\" maps to \"Alignment Guard,\" and \"validator\" maps to \"Seismic Processing\" or \"Medical Enclave.\" I'll also map to original details for specific IDs, enriching any API operation dynamically. I will dynamically generate specs and logs from the source data!\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:04.629Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Generating Dynamic Agent Metrics**\n\nI'm now implementing the dynamic generation of metrics like CPU usage, RAM, latency, uptime, and threads based on the agent's health or status. \"Active\" agents will have typical metrics, while \"warning\" or \"evaluating\" agents will receive different values. I'm also generating log entries with timestamps and relevant messages to simulate real-world data. I will be incorporating these dynamic fields as they are implemented, to generate the agent details.\n\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:07.219Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Simulating Metric Generation**\n\nI'm now generating dynamic metrics and log entries based on an agent's status. For \"critical\" or \"flagged\" agents, I'm generating values like CPU usage (90+), RAM (85+), and latency (80+). Log entries are also added for these states, indicating issues or warnings. For \"decoupled\" or \"offline\" agents, the metrics are set to zero, with a high latency value.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:08.346Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Operational Fields**\n\nI'm now examining the default operations from `lib/api-auth.ts`, looking closely at the structure and fields like `id`, `name`, `client_id`, `project_id`, `status`, `health`, and `agent_type`. This is in order to inform how to structure the mappings for an EnrichedAgent object. I'm taking notes on these fields to ensure a clear mapping and how to enrich the data, like the description or owner data. I'm focusing on \"Sovereign Audit Loop\" and will map the fields.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:10.175Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining Object Mapping Function**\n\nI'm now defining a helper function, `mapApiOpToEnrichedAgent`, to transform `ApiAiOperation` objects to `EnrichedAgent`. The function generates stable numbers from the `id` to avoid re-render jumps, and I have defined the logic for mapping the status based on `op.status` and `op.health`. I will also define and enrich the agent `type`.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:12.228Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Type and Stage**\n\nI've been refining the logic for mapping `agent_type` and now incorporating stages to my `EnrichedAgent` objects. I'm dynamically generating the type based on the agent type and a hash of the operation ID. Also I generate a random stage of the object, which I plan to incorporate. This gives a nice way to map values such as the \"Transport Node\".\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:14.521Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Simulating Metric Generation**\n\nI'm now generating dynamic metrics and log entries based on agent status, specifically for the \"evaluating\" state. I've adjusted the CPU usage, RAM, and latency values to better reflect this state. I'm also adding log entries that describe the ongoing policy verification and any observed warnings.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:16.669Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing Dynamic Logging**\n\nI'm now generating dynamic log entries based on the agent's status within the `mapApiOpToEnrichedAgent` function, and this builds on the previous metric and type generation work. These logs are designed to provide a real-world simulation of agent behavior. The logs will indicate any observed issues or warnings, as well as regular system updates. I've also added more descriptive messages to capture the status of each agent.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:18.622Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Metric Reporting**\n\nI'm now generating dynamic metrics and logging specifically for the 'evaluating' state. I've adjusted the CPU, RAM, and latency values to accurately represent this state. I've also incorporated a set of log entries that describe the policy verification and ongoing warnings. I am preparing to implement these states on the client side.\n\nI'm now generating dynamic log entries based on the agent's status.\nThese logs are designed to simulate real-world data and behavior and\nwill indicate observed issues, warnings, and system updates.\nI have added more descriptive messages to capture the status of each agent,\nincluding details from the current values.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
