{"ts":"2026-06-27T14:58:33.231Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Route Connections**\n\nI've checked the folder, and \"modal\" and \"detail\" don't appear in the content, besides the filename/route potentially. The route `/portal/ai-operations/[id]` is just a standard Next.js dynamic route, nothing special there, so far.\n\n\n**Defining the Visual Metaphor**\n\nI am now focused on defining the visual metaphor for the AI Operations portal. It's envisioned as a premium, zero-trust operator's cockpit, inspired by modern design principles. I'm thinking of circular telemetry rings displaying key parameters, a calm, clean aesthetic with monospaced UI elements and a specific color palette (`#009DFF`, `#00FFC2`). The goal is consistency with GFF AI's enterprise theme.\n\n\n**Outlining UI Structure**\n\nI'm currently outlining the UI structure, focusing on the main and detail pages. The main page will have a clean header, operation status, interactive telemetry filters, and a responsive grid for sandbox cards. Tabs will show telemetry ledger, hardware/enclave architecture, and governance/activity. The detail page will show KPIs, hardware details, eBPF logs, and attestation triggers. I'm also planning the loading, empty, error, and retry states. Finally, I will be planning the real-time client-side interactive filters next.\n\n\n**Planning Interactive Elements**\n\nI'm now planning the interactive elements. A \"Recycle Core\" button will trigger a local simulation of an enclave cold reboot with updating logs and animations. I'm also planning a \"Verify Attestation\" button which triggers a verified results display with animated progress states. I'm also planning the correct loading, error, and empty states. I'm taking the strategy of full mobile-first responsive design, utilising Tailwind grids.\n\n\n"}}
